mdo sde pa|Skt sautrāntika, sautrāntikaḥ\nZH 經量部 , 說經部 (jīng liàng bù , shuō jīng bù)\nEN sautrantika, Sutra School — One of the four systems of Buddhist tenets. To­gether with the Vaibhashika school, the Sautrantika is considered as be­longing to the Hinayana. The Sautrantikas are divided into two subgroups: the Sautrāntikas following scripture (lung gi rjes 'brang) and the Sautrāntikas following reasoning (rigs kyi rjes 'brang). The former group is quite close in outlook to the Vaibhashikas; the latter is particularly associated with Dharmakirti and is remarkable for its elaborate epistemology and logic. It is widely studied and utilized in Tibetan Buddhism. [IMW, 2004] One of the four systems of Buddhist tenets. Together with the Vaibhāṣika school, the Sautrāntika is considered as belonging to the Hīnayāna. The Sautrāntika is remarkable for its elaborate psychology and logic and is widely studied and utilized in Tibetan Buddhism. [TPQ, 2010] The name of a tenet system belonging to the Hinayana, notable for its elaborate system of logic and epistemology. [WL, 2012]\nFR Tenant des Soutras*, Sautrāntika (Tenants des Soutras)**, tenants des Soutras*, Sautrântika — école philosophique du Petit Véhicule.[POL, 1999] l'une des quatre écoles philosophiques du bouddhisme dans la classification tibétaine. Les Sautrântikas font partie du Petit Véhicule, comme les Vaibhâshikas. La pensée bouddhiste leur doit beaucoup en matière de psychologie et de logique. [TDPQ, 2009] [CC, 2013][SPB, 2020][LD, 2017]\nPT Sautrāntika (a), escola do Sūtra — Um dos quatro sistemas de princípios filosóficos budistas. Juntamente com a escola Vaibhāṣika, a escola Sautrāntika é considerada como pertencente ao Hinayana. Os sautrāntikas dividem-se em dois subgrupos: os sautrāntikas que seguem as escrituras (lung gi rjes 'brang) e os sautrāntikas que seguem o raciocínio (rigs kyi rjes 'brang). O primeiro grupo é bastante próximo dos vaibhāṣikas; o segundo está particularmente associado a Dharmakīrti e é notável pela sua elaborada epistemologia e lógica. É amplamente estudado e utilizado no Budismo tibetano. [IMW 2004].\nES Sautrantika, escuela del Sūtra
