rgyan drug|EN Six Ornaments — The six great commentators of the Buddha's teachings: Nagarjuna, Aryadeva, Asanga, Vasubandhu, Dignaga and Dharmakirti. [WOMPT, 1998] The six great Indian commentators of the Buddha’s teachings: Nagarjuna, Aryadeva, Asanga, Vasubandhu, Dignaga, and Dharmakirti. [TLWF, 2011] [NLF, 2005]\nFR Six Ornements — « six êtres qui embellissent l’univers » (GD) : Nāgārjuna, Āryadeva, Asaṅga, Vasubandhu, Dignāga et Dharmakīrti. [CGP, 1997]\nPT Seis Ornamentos — Os chamados “Seis Ornamentos”, ou "os seis grandes seres que adornam o universo”, são seis grandes mestres que escreveram amplamente sobre os ensinamentos do Buda, nomeadamente: Nāgārjuna, Āryadeva, Asaṅga, Vasubandhu, Dignāga e Dharmakīrti.\nES Seis Ornamentos — "Seis seres que embellecen el universo": Nāgārjuna, Āryadeva, Asaṅga, Vasubandhu, Dignāga y Dharmakīrti; los seis grandes comentadores de las enseñanzas del Buda.[PMP, 2002]\nIT Sei Ornamenti — Sei Ornamenti o ‘i sei grandi esseri che ornano l’universo’; sei grandi maestri che commentarono gli insegnamenti del Buddha: Nāgārjuna, Āryadeva, Asaṅga,Vasubandhu, Dignāga e Dharmakīrti.
rgyang 'phen pa|Skt cārvāka, āyata\nEN Charvaka — Name of an ancient Indian philosophical school professing materialistic nihilism. The Cārvākas denied causality, the law of karma, and the existence of past and future lives. [IMW, 2004] Members of an ancient Indian philosophical school professing metaphysical nihilism. The Cārvākas denied causality, the law of karma, and the existence of past and future lives. [TPQ, 2010] Members of an ancient Indian philosophical school that denied the law of karma and the existence of past and future lives.[NS]\nFR Cârvaka — membre d'une ancienne école philosophique indienne professant le nihilisme. Les Cârvakas niaient la causalité en général et plus particulièrement la causalité karmique, de même que la réalité des existences passées et futures. [TDPQ, 2009]\nPT cārvāka, materialista — Os materialistas ou cārvākas foram uma antiga escola filosófica indiana que defendia uma posição niilista e materialista. Os cārvākas negaram a lei do karma e a existência de vidas passadas e futuras.
